title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 94 Lever action 30-30.
location: 13 miles east in Deerfield, Madison, Wisconsin
postcontent:
This firearm was marketed through the Friends of NRA Program.

Each year at banquets across America, Friends of NRA chapters raise funds by auctioning or raffling firearms off.
Generally each year has its own set of firearms available through the program, usually specially embellished by an outside engraving firm.
But back in 1991 – the program was in its developing years and the firearms were ordered directly from Winchester, who did the embellishing itself.

You may be able to obtain further details on these rifles by contacting Winchester directly.
There was also a great deal of individual initiative by certain Friends of NRA chapters to get guns that were ever so slightly different in caliber or engraving.
Please note that we can provide no valuation figures on these arms as they were offered by auction and the winning bids varied greatly from auction to auction.

National Firearms Museum

Winchester Model 94 Lever action 30-30.  
New in the box…never fired.  Won at a NRA raffle in 1991.  
Inscribed with “Friends of NRA” “Celebrating 10 years”  On the other side are the Eagle and Flag in gold and an inscription about the 2nd amendment.    Serial number = 2NRA155.  
In earlier correspondence with Winchester…they indicated there were 825 guns like this produced in 1991.  More recent communication  gives me information like above but nothing about values.

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1903 30-06
postcontent:
The M1903 Springfield, formally the United States Rifle, Caliber .30-06, Model 1903, is an American clip-loaded, 5-round magazine fed, bolt-action service rifle used primarily during the first half of the 20th century.

It was officially adopted as a United States military bolt-action rifle on June 19, 1903, and saw service in World War I. It was officially replaced as the standard infantry rifle by the faster-firing semi-automatic 8 round M1 Garand starting in 1937. However, the M1903 Springfield remained in service as a standard issue infantry rifle during World War II, since the U.S. entered the war without sufficient M1 rifles to arm all troops. It also remained in service as a sniper rifle during World War II, the Korean War, and even in the early stages of the Vietnam War. It remains popular as a civilian firearm, historical collector's piece, and as a military drill rifle.

These rifles have been sporterized for over a century by gun smiths and prestigious firms such as Griffin & Howe and RF Sedgley. Who is to say who's carried this particular rifle in battle or where in the world it's been...if only it could tell its tales.

Rifle comes as pictured. $300 FIRM. No trades. Located in Enterprise.

 1915 Enfield MkIII* .303 Nazibuster. I've no idea what 'm doing, so feel free to correct any errors, but I make out "EFD" (R.S.A.F. Enfield, Enfield Lock) with a Nitro-proof mark below the serial number. And some other shit. Wood is dark but everything is in good shape. $350 +SH? Help a brother out.

 Hi-Point carbine, 9mm, one mag ATI stock. $250+shipping

 CZ52 7.62x25 Tok. You know you want a Tok, man. Hot little round, best sights I've seen on a combat handgun, and it's so clean it can pass an FBI background check. One mag. $250+SH

 Marlin 120 12ga pump, jeweled bolt, mid-bead. Good workhorse gun, 3.5" Magnum chamber. Perfect for knocking geese dead on the wing. Or throw some big slugs in there and kill a moose. Or a car engine. Seriously who needs a magnum chamber? You. You need a 12ga pump with a magnum chamber, because nobody likes geese. $250+SH

 Beretta A-L2, gorgeous motherfucking scattergat. I've neglected to get a full-length photo, but the whole thing is purdy. Finish is about as deep as a French indie film, just a beautiful gun. If I still shot sporting clays, I'd keep this one. $550+S&H

 Yugo SKS with grenade launcher and bayonet. Have some blanks around here somewhere. I'm not saying you should buy this, blanks, and one of the dummy grenades and shoot the dummy at shit, but ya know, you could. Really good condition here. $425+shipping, I'm beating out SAMCO and gunbroker here.

 Suomi 9mm carbine with ALL THE MAGAZINES. 2 drums, 7 stick mags, and no recoil. Boatloads of fun, and if you don't like the weight grab the SBR parts kit and get to stamping. There's $200 in mags here alone, and the last place I saw them they were $550. $750 shipped for all of it, and fuck me if that's not mostly shipping costs. **SPF**

 Glock 42 .380, less than 100 rounds through it, two mags with both factory springs and baseplates as well as the aftermarket +1 extensions. $425+S&H or trade for compact or subcompact Glock in 9mm, .40, .357 Sig

 COBRAY M11 9mm. Concealed carry? WE DON'T NEED NO CONCEALED CARRY! (1) 12rd mag, (4) hatesticks, case, and the massive fake can, all your for the low-low price of $500, that's right folks, $500+SH and you too can pretend to be an 80s action hero!

 Had enough 9mm carbines? No, you haven't Mechtech carbine kit with Korean hatesticks, ready to drop on to your G17/22/31 frame. Accurate, works, but the stock doesn't fit my oddly proportioned body. $250+shipping

 Catamount Fury II 12ga. Fixed "Dragunov" style stock, two 5rd mags, threaded for chokes. For what a Saiga costs unconverted you could send this motherfucker to whoever and have them Pimp Yo Ride. $500+S&H shipped takes it.

 Browning Auto 5 Light Twelve, 12ga, old and beautiful. Gold trigger. Hate to see it go, but I can't trust myself to own something this pretty, essentially since I have a hard-on to find a boogered one and SBS it Clyde Barrow style. $650+S&H

 Winchester Model 94 .30-30 Golden Spike Commemorative Edition, 1969 shipped to your FFL for $750.

 Bushnell Banner 3-8x, 1" tube on rings, perfect for a vintage rifle project. Old, but clear as day. $200+shipping

 Remington 742. I have one in .30-06 and one in .243, both in great condition, functional, and with vintage scopes on see-through mounts. Aught-six has a Redfield 3-9x and the .243 has a Weaver K4-1. Beautiful set perfect for a couple or father/mother and son/daughter, but I'll be willing to split the pair. $850 together or $450 each. Would recommend remounting the scopes, as the original owner had them on cockeyed.

 Other HiPoint carbine, late model 9mm, railed stock, two functional mags and one nonfunctional. $300+shipping

 BAR .30-06 with Redfield 3-9x on see-through mounts. Beautiful rifle, manufactured in early 1970. Some pitting on the bolt keeps this from being a thousand-dollar rifle. No engraving, so don't be afraid to take this out after your favorite megafauna. Some bluing rubbed away from the muzzle from traveling in a soft-case. $799 OBO.

 10-22. Yeah that 10-22. Wood, blued, one mag. $200. Also near the bottom is the optional Muzzlelite stock. $120 for the stock, $310 for all of it, plus shipping.

 Not pictured yet because I'm a dumbass and deleted the pictures is a gorgeous Weatherby Mk V in 7mm Wby Magnum. There's some wear at the muzzle from traveling in a case, but the bolt throws like a dream and the glass on top is clear as day. Zip-over protective case has kept the wood pristine, and the trigger breaks like glass. mm is a bit hot for my scrawny ass or I'd have thought long and hard about keeping it. Asking $999 for the rifle with scope [pics will be at the bottom of the gallery ASAP]. Also have several boxes of factory ammo for it at the reasonable rate of $2/rd.

 Have assorted ammo for most everything listed, but shipping ammo sucks so it's your call. As always, all laws apply, anything outside IL will require an FFL, anything in-state requires a FOID, waiting period.
